---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Why Ecosystem Approach - FraiseQL Architecture"
  description="Understand why FraiseQL is 11 tools designed to work together, not a single monolithic framework."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>Why Ecosystem Approach?</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>11 specialized tools multiply each other's performance. A monolith can't.</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Monolith Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Single-framework approaches try to solve everything in one codebase:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# Traditional framework (single tool)
fraiseql_monolith v1.0:
  ├─ GraphQL compilation
  ├─ SQL generation
  ├─ Query execution
  ├─ Migrations
  ├─ Test data generation
  ├─ Deployment orchestration
  ├─ Performance benchmarking
  └─ Schema linting

# Problems:
# - All features must share same language (usually Python)
# - Each feature is constrained by monolith architecture
# - Can't innovate independently
# - Code coupling increases technical debt`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #fef2f2; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>Result:</strong> Framework becomes bloated, features aren't best-in-class, hard to maintain.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Ecosystem Approach</h2>

      <p>
        Instead of one tool doing everything, 11 specialized tools working together:
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Core Layer (The Engine)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql</strong> – GraphQL compilation + execution (7-10× baseline performance)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-wire</strong> – Streaming JSON transport (200,000× memory efficiency)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>confiture</strong> – Fast migrations (600× faster database builds)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>Inner orbit: Essential to core functionality. These tools define what FraiseQL is.</em>
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Enhancement Layer (The Multipliers)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>pg_tviews</strong> – Incremental materialized views (2,083× faster queries)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>jsonb_delta</strong> – Efficient JSON operations (7× faster updates)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-seed</strong> – Intelligent test data (300× faster generation)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraisier</strong> – Deployment orchestrator (zero-downtime deploys)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>Mid orbit: Each multiplies the overall system's performance. Optional but recommended.</em>
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Support Layer (The Quality Multipliers)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-semis</strong> – Semantic UUID test data (alternative to fraiseql-seed)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-naming-police</strong> – Naming convention linting (prevents mistakes)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>velocitybench</strong> – 28-framework benchmarking (performance verification)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-ecosystem</strong> – Meta-analysis and strategic docs (understanding)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>Outer orbit: Supporting tools for specific needs. Pick what matters for your use case.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Why Specialized Tools Work Better</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">1. Focused Expertise</h3>
      <p>
        Each tool solves one problem perfectly:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-wire:</strong> Dedicated to streaming JSON efficiency. Best-in-class implementation because it's the ONLY thing this tool does.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>confiture:</strong> Focused on migrations. Not burdened by query execution logic. Can optimize aggressively.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>pg_tviews:</strong> Only cares about incremental view refresh. Can achieve 2,083× speedup through deep focus.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">2. Technology Choice</h3>
      <p>
        Each tool uses the best technology for its specific problem:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql (Rust):</strong> Performance-critical execution engine. Rust's zero-cost abstractions are essential.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>confiture (Rust):</strong> Fast migrations. Rust's speed matters for large schema files.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-seed (Python)</strong> Can use Python's scientific libraries (NumPy, Pandas) for smart data generation.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-naming-police (Rust):</strong> Linting is fast in Rust. Ships as single binary (no dependencies).
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>No single language is best for everything. Each tool uses the right tool for the job.</em>
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">3. Composability</h3>
      <p>
        Tools combine in powerful ways that a monolith can't:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# Development workflow
step 1: fraiseql compile schema.json → optimized SQL templates
step 2: confiture migrate → fast schema deployment
step 3: fraiseql-seed generate-data → intelligent test data
step 4: fraiseql-server start → execute queries
step 5: fraiseql-naming-police lint-schema → validate conventions

# Each tool outputs what the next tool inputs
# This composition isn't achievable in a monolith
# A monolith would need all these features built-in (bloat)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">4. Independent Innovation</h3>
      <p>
        Each tool can evolve independently without affecting others:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>pg_tviews improvement:</strong> Faster incremental refresh algorithm. Doesn't require updating fraiseql.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>fraiseql-wire update:</strong> Better streaming for Arrow Flight. Doesn't affect confiture.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>New tool (fraiseql-semis):</strong> Alternative to fraiseql-seed. Can coexist without conflict.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">5. Clear Boundaries</h3>
      <p>
        Each tool has a single responsibility:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>fraiseql = GraphQL → SQL compilation</li>
        <li>confiture = Schema versioning + migration</li>
        <li>pg_tviews = Incremental view refresh</li>
        <li>fraiseql-wire = Efficient wire protocol</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <em>Clear boundaries = easier to test, debug, and reason about each tool independently.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Performance Multiplication</h2>

      <p>
        The power of the ecosystem approach is that gains MULTIPLY:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`Base GraphQL execution:                          1×
+ fraiseql compilation:                        7-10×
+ fraiseql-wire streaming:                  ×200,000× (memory)
+ pg_tviews incremental refresh:             ×2,083×
+ jsonb_delta optimization:                    ×7×
+ confiture fast builds:                      ×600×
= Combined Ecosystem Benefit:              1.2M-63M×

Example: Processing 1M rows
Traditional:   1M rows × 200 bytes/row = 200MB in memory (garbage collects stall)
+ fraiseql-wire: Streaming 1M rows = 1MB buffered (constant memory)
Benefit: 200× better memory usage (enables 1B row analytics on same hardware)`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>Key insight:</strong> Individual tools deliver 2-2000× gains. Combined ecosystem delivers millions of times better.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        A monolith could have streaming JSON transport, but it would be burdened by all the other code. An ecosystem of focused tools achieves better engineering.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Ecosystem Usage</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Scenario: High-frequency trading API</strong>
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`Development:
  1. Write schema in Python decorators
  2. fraiseql compile → optimized SQL templates
  3. confiture migrate → zero-downtime schema deploy
  4. fraiseql-seed generate test-data → large realistic dataset
  5. fraiseql-naming-police validate → enforce conventions

Deployment:
  1. fraisier deploy → blue/green deployment
  2. fraiseql-server starts with pre-compiled schema
  3. velocitybench benchmark → verify 1000× improvement claim
  4. pg_tviews auto-refresh → materialized views stay fresh
  5. fraiseql-wire streams → responses as compact JSON

Monitoring:
  1. fraiseql-ecosystem analysis → understand performance bottlenecks
  2. confiture migration history → track schema evolution
  3. velocitybench trends → monitor performance over time`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #059669;">
        <strong>Result:</strong> Each tool excels at its domain. Ecosystem is greater than sum of parts.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Monolith vs Ecosystem Trade-offs</h2>

      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f5f3ff;">
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Dimension</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Monolith</th>
          <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Ecosystem</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Setup Complexity</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Simple (one tool)</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">⚠️ Choose which tools</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Feature Quality</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Compromise</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Best-in-class</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Performance</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Good</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Exceptional</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Evolution</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Monolithic updates</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Independent tools</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Technology Choice</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">One language</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Right tool per job</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background: #fafafa;">
          <td style="padding: 1rem; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;"><strong>Customization</strong></td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">Fork the entire project</td>
          <td style="padding: 1rem; text-align: center; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">✅ Replace individual tool</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Ecosystem Cohesion Score: 8.5/10</h2>

      <p>
        FraiseQL ecosystem tools are designed to work together, but they're not tightly coupled:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>10/10 – fraiseql ↔ fraiseql-wire:</strong> Wire protocol is the default transport. Designed together.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>9/10 – fraiseql ↔ confiture:</strong> Schema compilation → database migrations pipeline. Natural fit.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>8/10 – fraiseql-wire ↔ pg_tviews:</strong> Streaming large view results efficiently.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>7/10 – fraiseql-seed ↔ fraiseql-semis:</strong> Alternative approaches to test data. Complementary.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>5/10 – velocitybench ↔ fraiseql:</strong> Can benchmark other frameworks too (not tightly coupled).
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <strong>Cohesion score 8.5/10 means:</strong> Tools work great together, but each can be replaced or used independently if needed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Alternative: Build Your Own Stack</h2>

      <p>
        FraiseQL ecosystem is curated, but you don't have to use all tools:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Minimal (3 tools):</strong> fraiseql, confiture, fraiseql-wire – Core engine
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Standard (7 tools):</strong> Add pg_tviews, jsonb_delta, fraiseql-seed, fraisier
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Complete (11 tools):</strong> Add fraiseql-semis, naming-police, velocitybench, ecosystem analysis
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #666;">
        <strong>Choose your own adventure:</strong> Use only what benefits your specific use case.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Why Not a Monolith?</h2>

      <p>
        FraiseQL could have been a single Python framework like traditional ORMs:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`# What a monolith would look like
import fraiseql_monolith

# Single entry point, all features built-in
api = fraiseql_monolith.create_api(schema)

# Problems with this approach:
# 1. Streaming JSON transport needs Rust for performance
#    → Forces Python to call Rust module (FFI complexity)
# 2. Incremental view refresh needs deep PostgreSQL integration
#    → Would bloat Python framework with database-specific code
# 3. Deployment orchestration is Kubernetes-specific
#    → Not Python's strength, introduces too many dependencies
# 4. Performance benchmarking across 28 frameworks
#    → Requires language flexibility, Python not suitable
# 5. CLI tool needs to ship as single binary
#    → Rust/Go/Node.js are better than Python for this`}</code></pre>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; padding: 1rem; background: #fef2f2; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>Ecosystem approach:</strong> Each tool uses the best technology. Python for schema definition. Rust for compilation and execution. Result: best-in-class at each layer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>11 specialized tools multiply each other's performance. A monolith can't achieve this.</strong>
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>✅ Each tool uses best technology for its domain</li>
        <li>✅ Tools are focused and best-in-class</li>
        <li>✅ Independent innovation without coupling</li>
        <li>✅ Clear boundaries = easier maintenance</li>
        <li>✅ Performance gains multiply (1.2M-63M×)</li>
        <li>✅ Choose tools that fit your use case</li>
      </ul>

      <p style="margin-top: 2rem; padding: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4; border-left: 4px solid #059669; border-radius: 4px;">
        <strong>FraiseQL philosophy:</strong> Specialized tools working together beat a generalized monolith. This is why we're 11 tools, not 1 framework.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p style="margin-top: 3rem;">
      <a href="/why/database-first">← Back to Philosophy Guides</a> | <a href="/">Home</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
